goals.question: What is the trend of natural disasters over time?
goals.visualization: line chart of count by year
goals.rationale: This visualization will show the overall trend of natural disasters over time and help identify any patterns or changes in frequency.

goals.question: Which type of natural disaster has caused the most deaths?
goals.visualization: bar chart of deaths by disaster type
goals.rationale: This visualization will help identify which types of natural disasters are the most deadly and require the most attention in terms of prevention and response.

goals.question: What is the distribution of deaths across all natural disasters?
goals.rationale: This visualization will show the spread of deaths across all natural disasters and help identify any outliers or patterns in the data.

goals.question: What is the relationship between the number of deaths and the count of natural disasters?
goals.visualization: scatter plot of deaths by count
goals.rationale: This visualization will help identify if there is a correlation between the number of natural disasters and the number of deaths, which can inform disaster response planning.

goals.question: What is the distribution of natural disasters by type?
goals.visualization: pie chart of count by disaster type
goals.rationale: This visualization will show the proportion of each type of natural disaster in the dataset and help identify which types are the most common.

import seaborn as sns
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    data['Year'] = pd.to_datetime(data['Year'], format='%Y', errors='coerce')
    data = data.groupby('Year').sum().reset_index()
    sns.lineplot(x='Year', y='count', data=data)
    plt.title('What is the trend of natural disasters over time?', wrap=True)
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)

import seaborn as sns
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    data['Deaths'] = pd.to_numeric(data['Deaths'], errors='coerce')
    data = data.groupby('Entity')['Deaths'].sum().reset_index()
    data = data.sort_values('Deaths', ascending=False)
    chart = sns.barplot(x='Entity', y='Deaths', data=data)
    chart.set_xticklabels(chart.get_xticklabels(), rotation=45, horizontalalignment='right')
    chart.axhline(y=data['Deaths'].max(), color='r', linestyle='--', label='Max deaths: {:.2f}'.format(data['Deaths'].max()))
    chart.legend()
    return plt

chart = plot(data)

import seaborn as sns
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    data['Deaths'] = pd.to_numeric(data['Deaths'], errors='coerce')
    sns.histplot(data=data, x='Deaths', kde=True, color='blue')
    plt.axvline(data['Deaths'].median(), color='red', label='Median: {:.2f}'.format(data['Deaths'].median()))
    plt.legend()
    plt.title('What is the distribution of deaths across all natural disasters?', wrap=True)
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    data['count'] = 1
    disasters = data.groupby('Entity').sum().reset_index()
    plt.pie(disasters['count'], labels=disasters['Entity'], autopct='%1.1f%%')
    plt.title('What is the distribution of natural disasters by type?', wrap=True)
    return plt;
